So, while continuing to work with filtered display objects I've run across another potentially nasty bug. It seems that having a filtered object move on or off stage, produces flickering effect and on a less-than-high-end mobile device, the device may momentarily freeze or even crash and reboot.

I've created a very small app to reproduce the problem. All it does is generate a 64x128 image, applies a glow filter (any filter will produce the same results, but it is most noticeable with glow) and moves it back and forth over the left edge of the stage. If you run this on the desktop, you can notice some flickering and minor distortion of the glow filter. If you run it on a mobile device (so far we've produced the bug on a Samsung Galaxy S, iPad 2, and iPhone 4) though, you will get very heavy distortion of the filter and flickering of the entire screen. This is a screenshot of the image as it is leaving the stage: http://onebyonedesign.com/junk/stage_intersect.png . Of course, what you can't see in the screenshot is that the app locks up at that point for a couple seconds and occasionally does not unlock and crashes the device. I've pasted the code for the small 'app' here: https://gist.github.com/devon-o/5253405 .

What I suspect the problem is, is the excessive creation of textures as the image slides off the stage. The textures are created at the size of the rectangle that intersects with the stage and display object and then bumped to a power of two (meaning the closer the object is to the stage edge, the more often textures are generated).

So far, I've fixed the problem by replacing this bit of code in FragmentFilter.calculateBounds method:

sStageBounds.setTo(0, 0, stage.stageWidth, stage.stageHeight);
RectangleUtil.intersect(resultRect, sStageBounds, resultRect);

with this:

sStageBounds.setTo(0, 0, stage.stageWidth, stage.stageHeight);
if ( !(sStageBounds.intersects(resultRect)) )
    resultRect.setEmpty();

This isn't an optimal solution though. It's sort of all or nothing (if the display object intersects the stage, the filter texture is the size of the disp. obj. - otherwise, the filter is removed entirely), and misses all the optimization that was supposed to be there. But this way is a start for anyone having a similar problem.

In any case, it deserves to be looked at. :)

